  "why": "The paper does more than report failures: it analyzes the discovered failures in terms of distributional properties and connects those properties to underlying model weaknesses (distribution shift / class-distribution similarity). It (1) formulates and measures distribution difference (MMD) between generated test suites and class training distributions, (2) shows empirically that as MMD to a target class decreases the error rate and the fraction of errors predicted as that target class increase, and (3) demonstrates that these statistically-indistinguishable errors are harder for defenses to detect. It also shows that increasing distribution diversity (covering different MMD intervals and target classes) improves post-retraining robustness. These analyses trace failures to a concrete vulnerability — reliance on / brittleness to distributional differences between classes (i.e., distribution shift and class-overlap) — and thus provide actionable diagnostic insight.",
